In addition, there were {{ill|Gon-no-naishi-no-jō|ja|権掌侍|12=draft|12=draft}} ("provisional Naishi-no-jō") positions with two appointments, as well as an ad hoc position called {{ill|Naishi-dai|ja|内侍代|12=draft|12=draft}} to temporarily replace absent Naishi. Although no Naishi roles were directly assigned to the {{ill|Crown Prince's Household|ja|春宮坊|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Naishi-dai was permanently stationed there and would typically transition to a full Naishi position upon the prince’s enthronement.
== Naishi of the Saikū == These Naishi served in close proximity to the {{ill|Saikū|ja|斎宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, attending to her needs and responsibilities.
== Naishi of the Saiin == Similarly, the Naishi in the {{ill|Saiin|ja|斎院|12=draft|12=draft}} served the {{ill|Saio|ja|斎王|12=draft|12=draft}} in a comparable capacity to those of the Saikū.
== Naishi of Itsukushima Shrine == At {{ill|Itsukushima Shrine|ja|厳島神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Naishi were female shrine priests ({{ill|Miko|ja|巫女|12=draft|12=draft}}). Their duties included participating in rituals, reciting {{ill|Imayō|ja|今様|12=draft|12=draft}} to entertain noble guests who lodged at the shrine, and performing {{ill|bugaku|ja|舞楽|12=draft|12=draft}}. According to the "Itsukushima Michishiba-ki" ({{ill|厳島道芝記|ja|}}), the shrine maintained a hierarchical structure of Naishi from first rank (一﨟) to eighth rank (八﨟), collectively referred to as the "Yaotome" (八乙女) or "Hon-Naishi" (本内侍). Additional titles such as "Wagoto-Naishi" (和琴内侍) and "Karagami-Naishi" (韓神内侍) indicate a system of more than ten positions.
It is also said that {{ill|Mikohimegimi|ja|御子姫君|12=draft|12=draft}}, the seventh daughter of {{ill|Taira no Kiyomori|ja|Taira no Kiyomori|12=draft|12=draft}}, was born to Kiyomori and a Naishi of Itsukushima Shrine during his tenure as the governor of Aki Province.
