The head of the Naishi-no-tsukasa was called the {{ill|Shōji|ja|尚侍|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōji|qq=}} (alternatively read as "Naishi-no-kami"), with a limit of two appointments. The second-Ranking officials were the {{ill|Tenji|ja|典侍|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenji|qq=}} (Naishi-no-suke), with four appointments, while the third-Ranking officials, known as {{ill|Shōji|ja|掌侍|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōji|qq=}} (Naishi-no-jō), could also be referred to as "Naishi" in a narrower sense. There were four Shōji positions. Although there were no {{ill|Shuten|ja|主典|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shuten|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 四等官}} (clerks), the office followed a {{ill|Four-level official hierarchy|ja|四等官|1=Shitōkan制|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Four-level official hierarchy|13=User:Immanuelle/Shitōkan制|qq=}}.
In addition, there were {{ill|Gon-no-naishi-no-jō|ja|権掌侍|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gon-no-naishi-no-jō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} ("provisional Naishi-no-jō") positions with two appointments, as well as an ad hoc position called {{ill|Naishi-dai|ja|内侍代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Naishi-dai|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} to temporarily replace absent Naishi. Although no Naishi roles were directly assigned to the {{ill|Crown Prince's Household|ja|春宮坊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Crown Prince's Household|qq=}}, the Naishi-dai was permanently stationed there and would typically transition to a full Naishi position upon the prince’s enthronement.
== Naishi of the Saikū == These Naishi served in close proximity to the [[:en:Saikū|Saikū]], attending to her needs and responsibilities.
== Naishi of the Saiin == Similarly, the Naishi in the [[:en:Saiin (priestess)|Saiin]] served the [[:en:Saiō|Saio]] in a comparable capacity to those of the Saikū.
== Naishi of Itsukushima Shrine == At [[:en:Itsukushima Shrine|Itsukushima Shrine]], the Naishi were female shrine priests ([[:en:Miko|Miko]]). Their duties included participating in rituals, reciting {{ill|Imayō|ja|今様|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imayō|qq=}} to entertain noble guests who lodged at the shrine, and performing {{ill|bugaku|ja|舞楽|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bugaku|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 舞}}. According to the "Itsukushima Michishiba-ki" ({{ill|厳島道芝記|ja|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/厳島道芝記|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}), the shrine maintained a hierarchical structure of Naishi from first Rank (一﨟) to eighth Rank (八﨟), collectively referred to as the "Yaotome" (八乙女) or "Hon-Naishi" (本内侍). Additional titles such as "Wagoto-Naishi" (和琴内侍) and "Karagami-Naishi" (韓神内侍) indicate a system of more than ten positions.
It is also said that {{ill|Mikohimegimi|ja|御子姫君|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikohimegimi|qq=}}, the seventh daughter of [[Taira no Kiyomori]]{{citation needed |Taira no Kiyomori|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taira no Kiyomori|qq=}}, was born to Kiyomori and a Naishi of Itsukushima Shrine during his tenure as the governor of Aki Province.
